{"behaviors":[{"behavior_id":1,"description":"The request sent to the external API always includes the complete list of valid taxonomy labels.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is module handoff: classifier request builder -> API client payload. A pure unit of a helper could miss wiring/serialization omissions. REAL-INFRA/LLM-DEP are not required because this checks outbound payload shape, not live HTTP or model judgment. Rejected System because behavior text only requires that the sent request contain labels, which is verifiable with an in-process stub client. Rejected Agentic because correctness does not depend on model output content.","test_description":"Wire classifier module with a fake in-process API client that records outbound payload; invoke classify() and assert payload taxonomy list exactly matches configured labels (complete, no drops/reordering bugs if order matters).","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.35,"Integration":0.6,"System":0.03,"Agentic":0.02,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":2,"description":"When the API returns a label that is not in the taxonomy, the module returns \"unknown\" instead of forwarding the unexpected value to the caller.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Real failure is often at response-path handoff: API adapter parsing + normalization + public return path. A unit test of normalization alone may miss bypasses in orchestration. No real OS/network needed; no dependence on model quality. Rejected Agentic because behavior text focuses on handling an invalid returned value, which can be injected deterministically.","test_description":"Use in-process fake API client returning an out-of-taxonomy label (for example \"medical\"); call module entrypoint and assert returned label is exactly \"unknown\".","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.45,"Integration":0.5,"System":0.02,"Agentic":0.03,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":3,"description":"For identical raw API responses, the module's normalization step always produces the same final label.","minimum_level":"Unit","justification":"Behavior is explicitly local deterministic normalization logic for identical inputs. No module boundary is required to expose the failure; no infra or model call needed. Rejected Integration because behavior text scopes to normalization step itself, not cross-module state propagation.","test_description":"Call normalization function repeatedly with the same raw response fixture and taxonomy; assert output label is identical across runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.9,"Integration":0.08,"System":0.01,"Agentic":0.01,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"On repeated live API calls for the same document and taxonomy, the returned label remains consistent unless the provider response itself changes.","minimum_level":"Agentic","justification":"Behavior explicitly requires repeated live AI API calls and consistency relative to provider responses. Mocking would hide real model/provider variability and real response drift. This is not just transport/retry infrastructure; it depends on what the model/provider actually returns. Rejected Workflow because calls are repeated checks, not a chained multi-agent pipeline with dependent model decisions.","test_description":"Run N real classification calls against the live provider with fixed document+taxonomy, capture raw provider responses and final labels, and assert label changes only when raw provider response changes.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.05,"System":0.12,"Agentic":0.8,"Workflow":0.02}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"Request construction enforces the configured token budget before dispatch (for example truncate/reject according to policy).","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Failure boundary is